      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hot Summer Subways</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Medved letter complains of heat, noise, overcrowding and delays that dog New York City subway riders in summer (May 26 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Screeching Won't Come to Halt'' (news article, May 26):</p>
        <p>Another major problem that we subway commuters endure is poor ventilation and no air-conditioning at many platforms. When the weather gets hot, the heat gets trapped underground, and the temperature rises to 100 degrees and sometimes even more.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Screeching Won't Come to Halt'' (news article, May 26):</p>
        <p>Another major problem that we subway commuters endure is poor ventilation and no air-conditioning at many platforms. When the weather gets hot, the heat gets trapped underground, and the temperature rises to 100 degrees and sometimes even more.</p>
        <p>Now consider the situation when we have to wait 20 minutes for the train because of delays or skip a train because of overcrowding. I know many people who avoid using the subway system in the summer for this reason. Some days, I jump on any train just to get out of there!</p>
        <p>The screeching noise also gets worse in hot weather. The wheel lubricant can't take this heat either -- it evaporates.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL MEDVED  Brooklyn, May 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
